{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618095"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:19:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:19:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16491"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16491"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.95,0,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9182"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65496"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9182"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16491"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50935"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5083"},{"type":"tags","id":"8457"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21789"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21800"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65496"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary surfactant is essential for normal respiratory function. It is produced by specialised cells in the alveoli and contains a mixture of lipids and proteins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of pulmonary surfactant?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Facilitates gas exchange across alveolar membrane","Reduces surface tension at air-liquid interface","Maintains alveolar pH balance","Prevents fluid accumulation in alveoli","Protects against inhaled pathogens"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of pulmonary surfactant is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduce surface tension at the air-liquid interface\u003C/strong\u003E within alveoli. This prevents alveolar collapse during expiration and reduces the work of breathing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other available options are incorrect, as explained below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitates gas exchange across alveolar membrane\u003C/strong\u003E: gas exchange occurs by diffusion across the alveolar-capillary membrane and is not directly affected by surfactant. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintains alveolar pH balance\u003C/strong\u003E: alveolar and blood pH are regulated by the bicarbonate buffer system and respiratory rate, not by surfactant. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents fluid accumulation in alveoli: \u003C/strong\u003Efluid balance in alveoli is maintained by the balance between hydrostatic and oncotic pressures. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtects against inhaled pathogens\u003C/strong\u003E: while surfactant proteins have some immune functions, this is secondary to their surface tension effects. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurfactant is produced by type II pneumocytes and consists mainly of phosphatidylcholine (dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine) and other phospholipids, along with smaller amounts of surfactant proteins (SP-A, SP-B, SP-C, and SP-D).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary surfactant reduces surface tension in alveoli, preventing collapse during expiration.","Surfactant is composed primarily of phosphatidylcholine and other phospholipids.","Type II pneumocytes produce and secrete pulmonary surfactant."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50935"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16491"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50935"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T14:28:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T09:45:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9182"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65496"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedA